AlfariyDapu AlmuXarRakapu c
AlfariyDapu AlmuXarRakapu, (O, K, TA,) or AlmasoOalapu AlmaXarRakapu, (Msb,) for AlmuXarRaku fiyhaA, (Msb, TA,) is That [assigned portion of inheritance, or the question relating thereto (AlmasoOalapu AlmuXarRakapu being for masoOalapu AlfariyDapi AlmuXarRakapi),] in which the brothers by the mother's side [only] and those by [both] the father's and the mother's sides are made to share together; (O, Msb, * K, TA;) also called AlmuXarRikapu↓ [that makes to share], tropically;
(Msb;) and called also AlmuXotarakapu↓ [for AlmuXotaraku fiyhaA i. e. that is shared in]: (Lth, K, TA:) this is the case of a husband and a mother and brothers by the mother's side and brothers by the father's and mother's sides: (O, K, TA:) for the wife is half; and for the mother, a sixth; and for the brothers by the mother's side, a third, and the brothers by the father's and mother's sides share with them: (O, TA:) 'Omar decided in a case of this kind by assigning the third to two brothers by the mother's side, and not assigning anything to the brothers by the father's and mother's sides; whereupon they said, yaA Oamiyra AlmuWominiyna habo OanRa OabaAnaA kaAna HimaArFA faOaXorikonaA biqaraAbapi OumRanaA [O Prince of the Believers, suppose that our father was an ass, and make us to share by reason of the relationship of our mother]: so he made them to share together (faOaXoraka bayonahumo [thus in the O and K, but correctly faXarRaka bynhm, or, as afterwards in the TA, faXarRakahumo]): (O, K, TA:) therefore it (i. e. the fariyDap, TA) was called muXarRakap [and muXarRikap] and muXotarakap, [in the CK, erroneously, muXorakap,] and also HimaAriyRap: (K, TA:) and it is also called HajariyRap, because it is related that they said, habo OanRa OabaAnaA kaAna HajarFA muloqFI fiI AlyamRi [suppose that our father was a stone thrown into the sea]; and [therefore] some called it yamRiyRap: and it was called also EumariyRap. (TA. [More is there added, explaining different decisions of this case.])

XaniyEN c
XaniyEN Bad, evil, abominable, foul, or unseemly;
(S, O, Msb, K;) as also XaniEN↓ (O, K) and OaXonaEu↓, (S, O, K,) the last like Oakobaru in the phrase AallRehu Oakobaru, meaning kabiyrN, accord. to one of the two interpretations of this phrase: (O, TA:) pl. of the first XunuEN. (Msb, TA. *) It is applied to a day, in this sense: or as meaning disliked, or hated: (TA:) and so is OaXonaEu↓, (S, O, K, TA,) in the former sense, (TA,) or in the latter. (O, K, TA.) And you say manoZarN XaniyEN and muXanRaEu↓ [An aspect that is bad, evil, &c.] and AimoraOapN muXanRaEapN↓, meaning qabiyHapN [i. e. An unseemly, or ugly, woman]. (TA.) And AisomN XaniyEN [An evil, or abominable, name]: and qawomN XunuEu AlOasaAmiI [A people, or party, having evil, or abominable, names]. (A, TA.) And qiSRapN XanoEaMCu↓ [An evil, or abominable, or a foul, story]. (TA.) And gayorapN XanoEaMCu↓ Abominable, excessive jealousy: (O, K, TA:) in [some of] the copies of the K, erroneously, gbrp. (TA.)

2 XawRaca AlsRaHaAbu AlXRamosa c
2. XawRaca AlsRaHaAbu AlXRamosa The clouds covered the sun, (K,) as though it were turbaned with a dustcoloured haze inclining to yellow; as is the case in a year of drought; i. e. (T, L) thin clouds containing no water surrounding it, (T, L, K,) having the hue above described. (T, L.) ― -b2- XawRacat AlXRamosu [thus in the L and K, not XuwRicat nor taXawRacat,] The sun inclined to setting, (T, L, K,) and became covered with such clouds [as those above described]: (T, L:) became turbaned with clouds. (AHn, L.) ― -b3- XawRacahu, (inf. n. taXowiycN, L,) (assumed tropical:) He turbaned him; attired him with a turban: (AZ, T, L, K:) app.
from XwRct AlXms. (T, L.) And XwRc raOosahu (assumed tropical:) He turbaned his head. (Msb.)
